# f4a7145f4c3244b589505925a9e6be50
#: ../../admin-guide/monitoring/logging/log-formats.en.rst:23
msgid "Log Formats"
msgstr ""

# 1697dd24b45b40d7bc6a46ed8c2efeb5
#: ../../admin-guide/monitoring/logging/log-formats.en.rst:25
msgid ""
"This document provides a reference for all the different logging formats "
"|TS| supports. Rather than just reading about those formats, you may also"
" want to try our `online event log builder "
"<http://trafficserver.apache.org/logbuilder/>`_ for an interactive way of"
" building and understanding log formats."
msgstr ""

# 6866d559da6948dd9bf332e5b8aae22d
#: ../../admin-guide/monitoring/logging/log-formats.en.rst:31
msgid "Binary or ASCII?"
msgstr ""

# 6bcc694cc46c48a992ca97d8d9dabd81
#: ../../admin-guide/monitoring/logging/log-formats.en.rst:33
msgid ""
"You can configure |TS| to create event log files in either of the "
"following:"
msgstr ""

# 0665e6861cac4751aea803f99a13f113
#: ../../admin-guide/monitoring/logging/log-formats.en.rst:40
msgid "ASCII"
msgstr ""

# 84e0b78867af40d2b8f3608e35893b5e
#: ../../admin-guide/monitoring/logging/log-formats.en.rst:36
msgid ""
"These files are human-readable and can be processed using standard, off-"
"the-shelf log analysis tools. However, |TS| must perform additional "
"processing to create the files in ASCII, which mildly impacts system "
"overhead. ASCII files also tend to be larger than the equivalent binary "
"files. By default, ASCII log files have a ``.log`` filename extension."
msgstr ""

# c7ffa4ac06a444b1b06d0e3f0fbcd9e0
#: ../../admin-guide/monitoring/logging/log-formats.en.rst:47
msgid "Binary"
msgstr ""

# a7bfa73955a542f994f28fe2b5acbc76
#: ../../admin-guide/monitoring/logging/log-formats.en.rst:43
msgid ""
"These files generate lower system overhead and generally occupy less "
"space on the disk than ASCII files (depending on the type of information "
"being logged). However, you must use a converter application before you "
"can read or analyze binary files via standard tools. By default, binary "
"log files use a ``.blog`` filename extension."
msgstr ""

# 70429f331cde460199eeb9a2606068ce
#: ../../admin-guide/monitoring/logging/log-formats.en.rst:49
msgid ""
"While binary log files typically require less disk space, there are "
"exceptions."
msgstr ""

# 02f969f07a6641cea7cf471d60649859
#: ../../admin-guide/monitoring/logging/log-formats.en.rst:51
msgid ""
"For example, the value ``0`` (zero) requires only one byte to store in "
"ASCII, but requires four bytes when stored as a binary integer.  "
"Conversely, if you define a custom format that logs IP addresses, then a "
"binary log file would only require four bytes of storage per 32-bit "
"address. However, the same IP address stored in dot notation would "
"require around 15 characters (bytes) in an ASCII log file."
msgstr ""

# 8bd532b5ea5a47378c7e8ce4d5b6dc08
#: ../../admin-guide/monitoring/logging/log-formats.en.rst:58
msgid ""
"It is wise to consider the type of data that will be logged before you "
"select ASCII or binary for your log files, if your decision is being "
"driven by storage space concerns. For example, you might try logging for "
"one day using ASCII and then another day using binary. If the number of "
"requests is roughly the same for both days, then you can calculate a "
"rough metric that compares the two formats."
msgstr ""

# 2cf35864eb864a669e0e09106443f5bd
#: ../../admin-guide/monitoring/logging/log-formats.en.rst:65
msgid ""
"For standard log formats, select Binary or ASCII (refer to `Using "
"Standard Formats`_). For the custom log format, specify ASCII or Binary "
"mode in the :ref:`LogObject` (refer to :ref:`using-custom-log-formats`). "
"In addition to the ASCII and binary options, you can also write custom "
"log entries to a UNIX-named pipe (a buffer in memory) with the "
"`ASCII_PIPE File Mode`_ setting."
msgstr ""

# 9df69f72d4c34d5e9188dea19010e325
#: ../../admin-guide/monitoring/logging/log-formats.en.rst:72
msgid "Defining Log Objects"
msgstr ""

# 7c81341a15454e79aa75b8edf6aacdc7
#: ../../admin-guide/monitoring/logging/log-formats.en.rst:74
msgid ""
"To perform any logging at all on your |TS| nodes, you must have at least "
"one :ref:`LogObject` defined in :file:`logs_xml.config`. These "
"definitions configure what logs will be created, the format they will use"
" (covered in the sections :ref:`admin-monitoring-logging-format-standard`"
" and :ref:`admin-monitoring-logging-format-custom`), any filters which "
"may be applied to events before logging them, and when or how the logs "
"will be rolled."
msgstr ""

# 4d5975db9b8343598be324ae15d86317
#: ../../admin-guide/monitoring/logging/log-formats.en.rst:82
msgid "Log Filters"
msgstr ""

# bcb8672451804e8199a5ef357cfda959
#: ../../admin-guide/monitoring/logging/log-formats.en.rst:84
msgid ""
":ref:`LogFilter` objects, configured in :file:`logs_xml.config` allow you"
" to create filters, which may be applied to :ref:`LogObject` definitions,"
" limiting the types of entries which will be included in the log output. "
"This may be useful if your |TS| nodes receive many events which you have "
"no need to log or analyze."
msgstr ""

# 2588044ab18c400a9f95043b6883d56c
#: ../../admin-guide/monitoring/logging/log-formats.en.rst:93
msgid "Standard Formats"
msgstr ""

# 0f0614772d1e4e0ba4729272af436b3b
#: ../../admin-guide/monitoring/logging/log-formats.en.rst:95
msgid ""
"The standard log formats include Squid, Netscape Common, Netscape "
"extended, and Netscape Extended-2. The standard log file formats can be "
"analyzed with a wide variety of off-the-shelf log-analysis packages. You "
"should use one of the standard event log formats unless you need "
"information that these formats do not provide."
msgstr ""

